Duration token
==============


Abjad notes, rests, chords, tuplets and other durated components accept duration input in a couple of different formats.

* Abjad :class:`Rational <abjad.core.rational.Rational>` instances
* Python pairs
* Python `int` and `long` instances

For example:

<abjad>
note = Note(0, Rational(1, 4))
measure = RigidMeasure((1, 4), [note]) <hide
measure.meter.transparent = True <hide
staff = RhythmicStaff([measure]) <hide
write(staff, 'example1', 'oedo') <hide
</abjad>

And:

<abjad>
note = Note(0, (3, 8))
measure = RigidMeasure((3, 8), [note]) <hide
measure.meter.transparent = True <hide
staff = RhythmicStaff([measure]) <hide
write(staff, 'example2', 'oedo') <hide
</abjad>

And:

<abjad>
note = Note(0, 1)
measure = RigidMeasure((1, 1), [note]) <hide
measure.meter.transparent = True <hide
staff = RhythmicStaff([measure]) <hide
write(staff, 'example3', 'oedo') <hide
</abjad>


The Abjad **duration token** generalizes these different types of input.

Examples in the documentation that ask for valid duration token input accept any of the types of input show here.



.. note::

   Abjad does not count the Python `float` among the valid types of duration token.


